<br>
<br>
-----<br>
<br>
So I'm at my desk, trying to finish a grant proposal to get a lot of $$ from the State Dept.  A rather less-than-intelligent looking girl strolls into the front office and stands with a vacant stare on her face.<br>
<br>
&quot;Hi, where is the Institute of Religion?&quot; she says.<br>
<br>
Well, seeing how there are at least 14 different organizations here on the UC campus with some variation of that name, tell me a little more about what you need, I say.<br>
<br>
&quot;I'm Mormon.&quot; she replies.<br>
<br>
And I'm a Scientologist, but thanks for sharing.  Now, what does that have to do with it?<br>
<br>
After interrogating her for about 2 more minutes, I deduce she is in fact searching for the local top-secret military compound HQ of the Church of Latter-Day Saints.  &quot;Institute of Religion&quot; is the little title the Mormon church has given to it's churches, because, of course, their church is the only religion.<br>
<br>
So, I explain with crystal clarity the route to her compound--- church, excuse me.  <br>
<br>
Fifteen minutes pass.<br>
<br>
She strolls back in, looking even more baffled than before, if this is possible.<br>
<br>
&quot;I couldn't find it.&quot; she informs me, her bullish nosering and badly bleached hair distracting me from the problem at hand.  I contemplate why she's hunting for the church of Mormon.  Perhaps parents can now send them away for reform, much like fat camp.  <br>
<br>
And of course, if you're seeking enlightenment, or directions to your local cult, you should always be sure to stop by the Religious Studies Department.  All the sociologists and staticians and sanskritists here can answer all your questions about spiritual fulfillment.<br>
<br>
&quot;Hello?&quot; she asks me again, interrupting my moment of reverie.<br>
<br>
At this point, I lose any semblance of patience, courtesy, or professionalism.  I have just been on the phone with an irate professor who didn't realize shutting off her computer more frequently than once ever 2.5 years would help prolong the life of the fan and power source.  The computer problem is now my fault, of course.<br>
<br>
Reaching across the desk, I rip the Fall course catalog out of her pudgy little hands, tear the back cover with a highly detailed map of the campus off, and proceed to create a map so detailed and explicit, Ray Charles could follow it.<br>
<br>
At the stoplights, I write with my red pen in blazing block letters:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>RED MEANS STOP, YELLOW MEANS SLOW DOWN, GREEN MEANS GO.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
With large, jagged arrows, I mark her path down the campus roads, indicating which lane she should be in.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>TURN LEFT WHEN YOU SEE VOLLEYBALL NETS.  THERE IS SAND AND TWO LARGE POLES IN THE GROUND WITH A NET RUNNING BETWEEN THEM.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
At the approximate location of the compound, I sketch a fortress, complete with barbed wire and guard dogs, above which, giant red letters say:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>INSIMITUDE OF TEH RELOGGIN FOR MOMINS</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
The 'S'e are backwards.  This is so she will understand it.<br>
She nods in quiet understanding when I hand her the mangled treasure map and walks out the door.  <br>
<br>
As I almost click the &quot;Add Post&quot; button, I receive a phone call.  It's our lady Magellan again.  She swiped one of my business cards.  <br>
<br>
Now, what bothers me most is not that she's lost again, or even calling me, or even that she now knows my name, number, and place of work, but that she's driving and using a cell phone at the same time.  <br>
<br>
She's probably chewing gum, too.  <br>
<br>
&quot;I still can't find it.&quot; booms over the line.  <br>
<br>
Aim for a tree and step on the right pedal, I say.  I hang up and start finish the grant proposal the fedex guy is coming for in 15 minutes.<br>
